<li id="cite_note-45"><b><a href="#cite_ref-45" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web"><a href="http://books.google.com/books?id=PGdCAAAAIAAJ&amp;pg=PR16&amp;dq=%22common+era+of+the%22" class="external text" title="http://books.google.com/books?id=PGdCAAAAIAAJ&amp;pg=PR16&amp;dq=%22common+era+of+the%22" rel="nofollow">""common era of the birth of Christ" (1812)"</a><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://books.google.com/books?id=PGdCAAAAIAAJ&amp;pg=PR16&amp;dq=%22common+era+of+the%22" class="external free" title="http://books.google.com/books?id=PGdCAAAAIAAJ&amp;pg=PR16&amp;dq=%22common+era+of+the%22" rel="nofollow">http://books.google.com/books?id=PGdCAAAAIAAJ&amp;pg=PR16&amp;dq=%22common+era+of+the%22</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2007-12-14</span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=%22common+era+of+the+birth+of+Christ%22+%281812%29&amp;rft.atitle=&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DPGdCAAAAIAAJ%26pg%3DPR16%26dq%3D%2522common%2Bera%2Bof%2Bthe%2522&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Common_Era"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFHeneage_Elsley1812">Heneage Elsley (1812). <i>Annotations on the Four Gospels and the Acts of the Apostles (2nd edition)</i> (2nd ed.). London: A. J. Valpy for T. Payne. xvi.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Annotations+on+the+Four+Gospels+and+the+Acts+of+the+Apostles+%282nd+edition%29&amp;rft.aulast=Heneage+Elsley&amp;rft.au=Heneage+Elsley&amp;rft.date=1812&amp;rft.pages=xvi&amp;rft.edition=2nd&amp;rft.place=London&amp;rft.pub=A.+J.+Valpy+for+T.+Payne&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Common_Era"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-46"><b><a href="#cite_ref-46" title="">^</a></b> The term <i>common era</i> does not appear in this book; the term <i>Christian era</i> [lowercase] does appear a number of times. Nowhere in the book is the abbreviation explained or expanded directly. <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web"><a href="http://books.google.com/books?id=r7CbDH5hTe8C&amp;pg=PA75&amp;vq=era" class="external text" title="http://books.google.com/books?id=r7CbDH5hTe8C&amp;pg=PA75&amp;vq=era" rel="nofollow">"Search for <i>era</i> in this book."</a><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://books.google.com/books?id=r7CbDH5hTe8C&amp;pg=PA75&amp;vq=era" class="external free" title="http://books.google.com/books?id=r7CbDH5hTe8C&amp;pg=PA75&amp;vq=era" rel="nofollow">http://books.google.com/books?id=r7CbDH5hTe8C&amp;pg=PA75&amp;vq=era</a></span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Search+for+%27%27era%27%27+in+this+book.&amp;rft.atitle=&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3Dr7CbDH5hTe8C%26pg%3DPA75%26vq%3Dera&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Common_Era"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
